
# 2026-02-18 18:46:29.542627
+We just renamed and cleaned up a Python library called geepers-kernel (previously geepers-core, dr-eamer-ai-shared). It's a foundation library for a 72-agent system. Published to PyPI.
+
+What it has:
+- 14 LLM providers (Anthropic, OpenAI, xAI/Grok, Mistral, Cohere, Gemini, Perplexity, Groq, HuggingFace, ElevenLabs, Ollama, Gradient, Manus, ClaudeCode) via ProviderFactory singleton
+- Dream Cascade orchestrator (hierarchical 3-tier: 8 parallel workers → synthesis → executive summary)
+- Dream Swarm orchestrator (parallel domain-specific agents)
+- 18 data API clients (arXiv, Wikipedia, GitHub, NASA, PubMed, Census, etc.) via ClientFactory
+- MCP server (port 5060 SSE, port 5061 remote HTTP for Claude Desktop)
+- Flask web blueprints (LLM proxy, auth, CORS, health endpoints)
+- Tool registry (MCP-compatible schemas)
+- ConfigManager (env var + file precedence)
+- Utils: vision, embeddings, document gen (PDF/DOCX/MD), TTS, retry, rate limiting
+
+Recently done: renamed to geepers-kernel, v1.1.0, new README, cruft cleanup.
+Known gaps: phased workflow orchestrator, Bluesky AT Protocol client.
+
+Beyond these gaps, what else would you recommend? Focus on: developer experience, versioning, testing, packaging, observability, documentation, patterns commonly missing from multi-LLM foundation libraries.

